## Smart Contract

**`NeuroCredit.sol`** — deployed on Polygon Amoy Testnet

### Key Functions

```solidity
// ISSUER ONLY — mint a new Credit SBT
function mintCredit(
    address wallet,
    uint16  score,       // 300–900
    bool    eligible,
    string calldata metadataURI
) external onlyIssuer

// ISSUER ONLY — update score on existing SBT
function updateScore(
    address wallet,
    uint16  newScore,
    bool    eligible,
    string calldata metadataURI
) external onlyIssuer

// PUBLIC — lender verification (no personal data)
function verifyCredit(address wallet) external view returns (
    uint16  score,
    uint8   grade,       // 0=VeryPoor, 1=Poor, 2=Fair, 3=Good, 4=Excellent
    bool    eligible,
    uint32  updatedAt,   // unix timestamp
    uint256 tokenId
)

// PUBLIC — check if a wallet has a SBT
function hasSBT(address wallet) external view returns (bool)

// LOCKED — SBTs cannot be transferred
function transferFrom(address, address, uint256) external pure {
    revert("NeuroCredit: SBTs are non-transferable");
}
```

### What Makes This SBT Special

| Property | How it's enforced |
|---|---|
| Non-transferable | `transferFrom` and `safeTransferFrom` revert at contract level |
| One per wallet | `require(!_hasSBT[wallet])` on mint |
| User ownership | Token lives in wallet, issuer cannot recall it |
| Score updatable | `updateScore()` refreshes without burning |
| Private by design | Zero personal data stored on-chain |

---

## Frontend Pages

The app is a single `index.html` file — no framework, no build step, instant load.

| Page | Path | Description |
|---|---|---|
| Home | `/` | Hero, stats, feature cards |
| Get Scored | `#apply` | 14-signal submission form with live sliders |
| Score Result | Modal | Animated gauge, breakdown bars, mint button |
| Verify | `#verify` | Lender verification portal |
| How it Works | `#how` | 5-step explainer |

### Offline Fallback
The JavaScript scoring engine in `index.html` exactly mirrors the Python model logic. If the FastAPI backend is unreachable, scoring still works — making the demo bulletproof for presentations.

